\par }\pard \ql \fi-480\li480\ri0\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\tx502\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin480\itap0\pararsid12069192 {\f0\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033\insrsid12069192\charrsid2039529 I:\tab 
Could you tell me your name and present address please?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Do you want me full name. My name is Mrs Grace - Grace Bessie B., Mrs, S. Street, Camberwell, SE5.
\par I:\tab Could you tell me your year of marriage?
\par GB:\tab Yes, December 1922.
\par I:\tab Could you tell me your year of birth and where you were born?
\par GB:\tab I was born 1901 in Peckham.
\par I:\tab How many years did you live in the house you were born in?
\par GB:\tab That I cannot know - I do not know. But at the age of three - I wasn't - we were not living in that house, so it'd be about three-year - three years I suppose, yes.
\par I:\tab Where did you move to from there?
\par GB:\tab Well we went into a turning called Greylands Road that was also in Peckham.
\par I:\tab How long did you live in Greylands Road?
\par GB:\tab Until I was about six I think.
\par I:\tab Where did you go from there?
\par GB:\tab Well from there we went to - went to - where I was married from - Weight Street, and that was in Camberwell.
\par I:\tab So you lived in Weight Street from the age of six?
\par GB:\tab Six until I was married, yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Can you remember why the family made these moves?
\par GB:\tab Yes, I can, 'cos they got cheaper rents. As we moved out you see the room - room - the rents were cheaper see.
\par I:\tab How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par GB:\tab I had - I had - four sisters, which I have now and I had three brothers, which I have not now. They're - all dead.
\par I:\tab Could you tell me what their ages are or their spacings?
\par GB:\tab Yes, I can, you - would you like me to tell you? My - now I'm seventy, my - my - brother who all died as well you mean, all of them? Yes, well my - yes, I will, I can come down better like that, 
yes. My - my - my brother Arthur, if he was alive would be seventy-three. I am seventy. My next - and spaced about every two years, and that was - I can go through them, Arthur, Grace, Maude, Florrie, Hilda, Charlie, Jack and Ernest. Two years between all
, yes.
\par I:\tab Do you know how old your father was when you were born?
\par GB:\tab Yes, I think I can tell you that. About twenty-two.
\par I:\tab Where did he come from?
\par GB:\tab Well he originally came from - Manchester. But course he'd lived in - he lived in London practically all his life but he - I think he was born in Manchester, yes.
\par I:\tab His parents moved down here?
\par GB:\tab Moved down here, yes.
\par I:\tab What was his occupation?
\par GB:\tab He was a wheelwright.
\par I:\tab Did he have any other occupation before or after this?
\par GB:\tab No, the only thing I ca
n think of he used to be an amateur boxer, but apart from that I can't remember, because he was always - he used to make - I'll tell you, he worked for Thomas Tillings here, they used to make the big wheels for the buses, - the horse buses. That's what he
 used to do you see. He was the foreman at - that time.
\par I:\tab Did he also do any casual or part time jobs?
\par GB:\tab Only this.
\par I:\tab Only boxing?
\par GB:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember your father being out of work at all?
\par GB:\tab No.
\par I:\tab He had regular employment?
\par GB:\tab Yes, but he used to have short times. But - never really out of - not really out of work.
\par I:\tab How old was your mother when you were born?
\par GB:\tab My mother was about a year younger than my father. Oh no - when I was born - oh - let me see - my - I've got to work this out - m
y - in 1945 my mother died and she was sixty-seven. Yes? She - she must have been about - when I was born you mean? Well I was born in 1901 and I think she was born - she was married about a year before. You know, the usual run of things, you marry and yo
u get a child so quickly.
\par I:\tab That would have been about a year before Arthur?
\par GB:\tab That's right, yes.
\par I:\tab Where did she come from?
\par GB:\tab Oh my mother was born in London. In Bermondsey, yes.
\par I:\tab Did she work before she got married?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, she went to work when she got - when she first got married. She was a milliner, Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she work at all after she was married?
\par GB:\tab Well, yes, but at all those - part time jobs you know where the children could be minded, it wasn't the regular w
ork but she worked place like R. Whites where they used to make the - the lemonade and washing bottles and all that sort of thing. To help - help to keep us going you see. Oh yes. She used to - I can remember her in her - coarse apron. Oh - when you look 
at it now it's really terrible what she had to put up with, and we always used to try to pull our weight 'cos we were only kids.
\par I:\tab What sort of hours did she work on these part time jobs?
\par GB:\tab Well, sometimes - well, sometimes they used to be at six o'clock in the morning. See, and they work up 'til dinnertime you see.
\par I:\tab Would it usually be more like this long morning?
\par GB:\tab Yes, yes, well you see and it was more in the summer because they were selling soft drinks being - being drunk in the summer, yes.
\par I:\tab Did she do any other sort of part time work apart from this factory work?
\par GB:\tab Well the usual part time that most working women did that when another woman had a baby they'd - all take a turn in - and they'd say - one would come and say, I'll take the childre
n - kids, I'll take the kids, I'll take the washing - you take that. And if the word money was mentioned - no, no one wanted paying, everybody did for everybody else. Another thing, if a man was out of work at Christmas - they'd - about - so - before Chri
s
tmas they would - put a - a subscription, so that that family never went without its Christmas. They always see to the children, always saw to the children, and the door could stand open all day and nobody would enter. But not you - that's how days were t
hen. There was a wonderful spirit of comradeship and neighbourliness, which is no longer here. No. Marvellous it was.
\par I:\tab Who looked after the children when your mother was at work, would this be neighbours or what would happen, that was your job was it?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. I'm the oldest you see, oldest girl you see. I never knew what it was to be a child.
\par I:\tab How many rooms were there in the house in Weight Street?
\par GB:\tab Well there were six. But there was two up the top that we let to somebody else.
\par I:\tab So you really had four?
\par GB:\tab Well really, to be quite honest, three - three rooms and a scullery.
\par I:\tab This would be two bedrooms?
\par GB:\tab A living room and a scullery. That's right.
\par I:\tab How about bathroom and toilet?
\par GB:\tab Well we had an indoor toilet but you must be joking about
 a bathroom. Unheard of. Do you know where we used to have our bath? We had rather fair sized kitchenette and an old fashioned black gas stove, big bath, that shape, not the long - bungalow baths. Mother used to put - pails - gallon and a half pails on th
e gas, open the gas oven door, put the water in and you had your tubs, and as one come out a drop more was put in and vice versa. But we all had our bath.
\par I:\tab This was the big oval bath?
\par GB:\tab Yes, you know, with two handles each end, you know, they were very big. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters live with you in the house?
\par GB:\tab Not lived with us, only there were two lodgers upstairs, a Mr and Mrs - oh - Stedman I think it was used to live up there. But of course we never wen
t up there because it was on a little floor of its own. But my mother was the landlady of the house, you know, she was the tenant, but my mother let the rooms. Well they had to let rooms in those days. They couldn't afford to pay the rent themselves. You 
could always get rooms in those days you know. Used to see it on the door, rooms to let, on the windows, you know, in whitening.
\par I:\tab Did you have much to do with these lodgers?
\par GB:\tab Well they had to come downstairs for water and they had to use our toilet. Bu
t they had a little gas stove on the landing and - could do their own cooking. And they had a little place in the garden where they used to keep their coal, they had two flights of stairs to come down and get it. But then you see all us kids used to help.
 
You see, Mrs Stone - Mrs Stedman come to the door, she'd say, could one of the children bring me up some coal? And my mother's say - take the coal up, you see, and we went and took it. It was a recognised thing that you helped other people when they were 
getting on.
\par I:\tab They were fairly elderly people were they?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab But they did have their own meals separate?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. Oh yes. Entirely on their own, they didn't live with us at all, no.
\par I:\tab How much rent would you pay for two rooms like that in those days?
\par GB:\tab Yes, about five shillings.
\par I:\tab Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house at all?
\par GB:\tab You must be joking. No, only - only us, we - we always helped in the house, yes - with the children and all that, yes, we all worked in - no, my mother couldn't afford a - anything like that. Unheard of.
\par I:\tab Was the washing done at home or sent out?
\par GB:\tab It was not done at home, it was taken out, and it was taken out to the public baths. And as a matt
er of fact they still run the public baths now - in Camberwell. Used to take it out on a - on a bus naturally, and it used to be done. Two coppers there and they used to boil it up and wash it, dry it and then bring it home. Because you had no facilities 
as such, we had a little tiny yard, not big enough to dry it, and being a big family it used to go to - to - the laundry - to the - not launderette they weren't - they were public wash baths - public wash houses.
\par I:\tab Could you iron the things there?
\par GB:\tab Yes, in some parts yes, if you cared to stay you could iron them, it'd be - it wouldn't be - electric irons, it would be the old fashioned flat irons, yes.
\par I:\tab Did you usually do it all there or did you do the ironing at home?
\par GB:\tab Well sometimes we did it at ho
me, it's all according how long a time my mother could spare to stay there you see. If, of course with all us to see to and then of course - and of course in the old days, when she used to bring it home sometimes you know the iron, putting them on the gas
 
and all that, well they had the old fashioned mangle, and the big sheets and things like that weren't ironed they used to go through the mangle. You see them sometimes in the old fashioned, on television, old-fashioned houses where you see the big wooden 
mangle.
\par I:\tab Did your mother or father mend or make any of the family clothes?
\par GB:\tab No, didn't make - no, my father didn't, my father was - didn't do anything like that. My father was one of them - man apart, he never even took us out or never even took my mot
her out, he - he was the boss, yes, he went out nearly every night but not - my mother - we used to do - mend, we had a - a little machine that we could mend with or - if we got - we'd - the cut downs from one to the other, we used to do all that sort of 
thing and of course as we got older we could have material, my mother would make a dress, but then it was the trouble of getting hold of the stuff you see. You couldn't afford it.
\par I:\tab Were your clothes new or second-hand?
\par GB:\tab Well - I usually - my being the 
eldest, I usually used to get the new and as I grew so they went down. But - otherwise we might get - that's how it worked out you see, 'cos the - when it got too - when I grew out of it it come to my sister - sister you see. I think then the younger one 
got - bit more - new because then that come for the other one you see.
\par I:\tab But you didn't get your clothes from a second-hand shop, you passed them down within the family?
\par GB:\tab No. Oh no, no, no. No, didn't do that, no.
\par I:\tab And this would be the same for shoes?
\par GB:\tab 
Well no, not quite, not really because you - you - you used to be able to get few shoe's from the school. Not shoes, boots. And - then the - they used to be free if they decided that the income was that low they used to be free. Well then you - when 
you wore them a bit, your feet got too big, then you passed them on too. But - then the rest of them of course you have to buy for the little ones. Yes. Oh yes, you do that sort of thing.
\par I:\tab You say your father was boss in the house?
\par GB:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Would he do anything at all?
\par GB:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Like washing up?
\par GB:\tab No. You mus
t be joking. My father? My - my father came - we all had to be in bed before my father come home from work so he could have his tea in peace. Oh yes. We never saw our father, only on a Saturday and a Sunday because we - he used to leave home at six o'cloc
k in the morning, 'cos they used to in those days, before six to be at work at six, and we never saw him until weekend. And he came in every night of his life if he was - providing he was well - wash and dress himself up.
\par I:\tab And you had to be in bed?
\par GB:\tab Before he came home. If he came home - he'd get in about half past six and we'd be all in bed. Oh yes.
\par I:\tab So you had an early bedtime?
\par GB:\tab We did. That's why I can get up so early in the morning now without - that's a fact. I can, I can - I can - I've never 
- I've worked on the railway for years and I've never once had to have an alarm clock. I come up here of a night with a watch. I've got so brainwashed into getting up and going to bed and - and when I get to a certain time at night I've got to go to bed, 
because I get tired. But I can get up any time in the morning, if it's two o'clock I can do it. Even now.
\par I:\tab How long did this last, that you had to go to bed before your father came home?
\par GB:\tab Oh - well when we grew - when we grew older, like I'm talking about when we were young children you see, but as we grew older of course we stayed up.
\par I:\tab About what age would you say the change came?
\par GB:\tab Well I suppose I'd - we'd be about ten or eleven then and then he had us - but even then the young ones went to bed. 
Oh yes, until they grew older and - then of course when we grew older of course we - we couldn't go to bed at that time. But my father used to like - used to - but I'll tell you another thing, which we used to hate, Sunday mornings. We stayed in bed 'til 
h
e had his breakfast. Oh we used to hate it. And then - when he'd had his breakfast and was gone off to wash and everything then we'd come down and get ours. Half a kipper. Oh Sunday morning breakfast was something. All the week we had bread and dripping o
r bread and jam, something like that, but on a Sunday morning we'd get perhaps a half a kipper or a piece of - of haddock, she'd get it so cheap those days you see. Get - you could get kippers three a pair. Yes.
\par I:\tab Would your father do any decorating?
\par GB:\tab N
o, well he - well when - when it wasn't your place you didn't do that. But my father was a rather a - bicyclist. He used to go - he - and he took great care of his bicycle as if - as the men do with their cars now, and my husband did with his bicycle - my
 father did with his bicycle, he used to - he used to go to work on it, on his bicycle, yes, look after it. But that was his hobby, he used to go round riding quite a bit.
\par I:\tab Did he ever undress or bathe any of the young children?
\par GB:\tab Never.
\par I:\tab How about reading or telling stories?
\par GB:\tab Never. He had nothing to do with us much at all. Except - except that he was the cause of our existence, that's all. Yes, yes, that's right.
\par I:\tab What sort of tasks did you have to carry out regularly in the home?
\par GB:\tab Well we us
ed to - well on Saturday we all had to do - we had a house with steps so one had to - I had to clean - the other girls had to clean all the steps down. Then we had to clean the knives and - used to clean the knives and forks. And them there.
\par I:\tab And all the children as they got old enough had some job to do?
\par GB:\tab Oh all - that's right. Job to do, oh yes, you always had your regular jobs.
\par I:\tab Did the older children help the younger ones with things they found difficult, like dressing or eating?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, well we had to, my mother couldn't do it, oh yes, we always looked after, the - oh always looked after the little ones. Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Would the younger ones do things to help you, as you got older and went to work?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. Well - well, we didn't want them to 
do anything to help us 'cos we - but when we - when we started going to work that made things a little easier, 'cos even - even only half a crown a week coming in made a great deal of difference to the - to the family you see.
\par I:\tab When you got old enough to stay up after your father came home what time was bedtime then?
\par GB:\tab Oh I used to go to bed about half past eight - nine, you see it's all according if - if me mum and dad was out, when dad decided he'd take mum out, well we used to - go into - we used to 
go into mum's bed with the baby, 'cos we didn't have much room with being a nice big family, used to go into bed with the baby until they come in and then we'd - leave the baby there and go back to your own bed when - they went to bed you see.
\par I:\tab At what age did you put yourself to bed?
\par GB:\tab Oh we put ourselves to bed - quite young, we used to have to get - oh yes, get undressed and told to get - go and get yourself washed - oh quite small. You had to because there was so many on steps and stairs.
\par I:\tab You must have been rather cramped for sleeping?
\par GB:\tab We were cramped - we were cramped for space.
\par I:\tab Did you share the bedroom or bed with anyone?
\par GB:\tab Oh - yes, I'll say we did. My - my eldest brother - 'cos my - there was a great deal of difference betwe
en the two - the boys you see. My brother elder and then the other once came right down the - and so he had a - in those days what they used to call a bedchair in the big living room. There was my father and mother and the baby in one room, and there was 
- three of us in one bed, big bed, and two in a cot. That's how it worked there.
\par I:\tab What was a bedchair?
\par GB:\tab Well it was a - in those - what you would - a chairbed it was called, but it used to be all iron and it used to - you could fold it up and put it aw
ay, and then fetch it up and bring it out you see at each night, it would fold. Folding - they used to call 'em folding bedchairs. Remember my oldest brother used to sleep on there, I don't know how he managed it but he did.
\par I:\tab You used to bath in the kitchen?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, in the kitchen - in the kitchenette, yes. Well it wasn't called a kitchenette - scullery in those days, no such things as posh as kitchenettes.
\par I:\tab How often would you have a bath?
\par GB:\tab Every - oh - once a week. Yes, just once a week, we had that, oh yes. Friday nights was bath night. Oh yes.
\par I:\tab How about clean clothes?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Oh yes, we used to - oh, my mother was very fussy about her washing. Yes, always had nice clean clothes, we always - 'cos - well we all helped you see, if mother'd do
ne the washing and she didn't stop to do the ironing well we'd be - there'd be one turning the mangle while the other was pushing 'em through and then - we used to iron them ourself you see.
\par I:\tab Where did the family have their meals?
\par GB:\tab In the - in the kitchen - in the big kitchen. Not in - yes, not in the - we had a - we had two bedrooms you see and a - a kitchen and then there was the scullery, you see, so we had it in the kitchen, 'cos that was a fair sized room.
\par I:\tab Were there any occasions when you ate in another room?
\par GB:\tab Well we had no other room to eat in.
\par I:\tab What sort of cooking equipment was there, was it gas?
\par GB:\tab Yes, gas. Yes, they - but no - oh, never had electric. No it's gas, and there's - there was a - in those days you never had your own gas 
stove or anything, there was a black - black things and you used to polish 'em with black lead and all that. And then in that same kitchenette or scullery, we had a little cooking range, you know, with an oven. So.
\par I:\tab This was coal was it?
\par GB:\tab Yes. So in the winter mother used to bake in there. But in the summer she used to mostly use the gas oven you see.
\par I:\tab What time was breakfast eaten?
\par GB:\tab Well - my father used to have to be up pretty early mornings so we didn't have our breakfast with him, but we had o
ur breakfast about half past seven, quarter to eight, 'cos you see we had to be at school by nine or quarter to nine. 'Course it isn't the same as it is today, we had different hours to what they have now. Nine 'til twelve and two 'til four. And when you 
- we came upstairs in the school - in the - in the school - in the - when you became over eleven you went upstairs and then you stayed 'til two - two 'til half past four.
\par I:\tab Would your mother be there at breakfast time?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, mother would see that we had our breakfast. Unless of course she was working then I - then I had to see to it you see. Yes, that's right. And I'd take the baby round to the lady to mind while we all went - the rest of us went to school.

\par I:\tab What did you have for breakfast as a rule?
\par GB:\tab Well - all the week mostly it was bread and - not butter, we didn't know what butter was - bread and jam, then we used to buy - go out and take a cup to the shop get a penn'orth. And - on Sundays it was a - as
 I say a - a - piece of kipper or something like that or - 'cos so could get eggs very cheap then, sometimes twenty-four for a shilling and - then you could have egg or something like that you see. But it was a - and we never - I say we never knew what co
ws milk was, it was always goats milk, it was in a tin you know. We never ever saw a - a milk -
\par I:\tab Did you notice the seasons much more with food those days?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Yes, yes, you did, 'cos there was no refrigeration or anything of that sort you know, yes,
 you did - you noticed the - there was this here - tradition of not eating pork unless it got an 'r' in the month and - and all - and all those sort of things you know, and then when - then there was the time you noticed when - they'd say - oh, be able to
 
get some cheap fish, the - herrings are in. All those sort of things you knew, see. You knew - and - to be quite, honest it seems as if even the weather was different. Because I can remember holidays in school time when you - the whole month would absolut
ely be gloriously hot. Used to go to the park all day then with a bottle of milk and - a bottle of cold tea and sandwiches for the day. Yes.
\par I:\tab Where did you have your midday meal?
\par GB:\tab In the kitchen, indoors.
\par I:\tab You used to come home from school?
\par GB:\tab Yes, 
well in those days there wasn't - school meals as such as there are now but there was the - the charity - where you could have - if your circumstances were a - you could get - a bowl of soup and a piece of bread, you see, free. But of course that was - yo
u
 were terrible - that was thought terrible of. Oh yes. Charity. And you knew it. And - and there was one time when I know - know my father had been ill and he hadn't - didn't get paid in those days, well we had to have it and it was terrible 'cos everyone
 
- charity - oh. We only had one girl in our school - in our class that had a - a - a drill slip, you know, like - what they're all moaning about having to wear now. Oh that was all the go, and I used to look at it and say, oh I'd love to have one of them.
 I did. But she used to look lovely. Yes.
\par I:\tab What would you usually have for a midday meal?
\par GB:\tab Well mother used to - my mother used to make an awful lot of stews and meat puddings and meat pies, because there was a - a butchers near where we used to live a
nd you had to go early in the morning and he'd wrap you up a big paperful of meat for tuppence. Then you'd go into the greengrocer, they all opened early, you used to get what they called penn'orth of pot-herbs, that was carrots, onions and turnips, you s
e
e. A little bit of suet. To make some dumplings, she had the flour. And you know you could get a really good meal for all us lot for about a shilling. The lot of us. And if my mother was at work she'd do that - she'd get that and - I'd go - we'd go and ge
t that the morning before and my mother'd cook it that night so that when we come home it only had to be warmed through.
\par I:\tab Did you have anything special on Sunday midday?
\par GB:\tab Oh - oh, we - oh we always had a little joint on a Sunday, yes. 'Course meat was 
very - very cheap then you know. Not like it is now. With veg. And me mother always used to make yorkshire pudding, don't matter what it was, what meat it was, my father liked yorkshire pudding. And - always had yorkshire pudding. And another thing I used
 
to hate to. My father used to like his beer, so he used to go to pubs and they wouldn't close 'til three on a Sunday, well therefore we went to Sunday school without our dinner, because the dinner had to be ready for him. And then - ours was put in the ov
en 'til we came home at four o'clock. Yes. But we didn't know any different you see so we just accepted it you see. Didn't know any different.
\par I:\tab What would be the typical evening meal?
\par GB:\tab Well - my mother used to make - big - big cakes you know with a lot
 of fruit and all that in and - then we had - that was the day that we had best jam as we used to call it, instead of having out of the big jar, we used to have a little bit of a - maybe a - well we didn't buy it in jars then, bought it always in this - w
e used to go with a cup - and we used to have jar - a little jam on one of these big cakes you see and then when the tomatoes were very cheap, which they were in those days, it was salad. You could get a penny - you could get a penny lettuce you see.

\par I:\tab Did you eat as much salad stuff in those days as they do now?
\par GB:\tab No. No. No, less of that, yes. It was more what we used to - 'course my father used to call that rabbit's food, see, it used to be more substantial. My father always used to eat - shrimps and winkles and that sort of thing on Sunday you see.

\par I:\tab Did you used to have them as children?
\par GB:\tab Well - yes, sometimes, because they were only tuppence a pint you see.
\par I:\tab Did your mother bake her own bread or make her own jam?
\par GB:\tab No. She never had a chance, with all them kids.
\par I:\tab What about home made wines or beer?
\par GB:\tab No. That always come from the local. That's why none of us I think - not any of my sisters or brothers drink, they're all teetotallers. Not one of us drinks. We had enough of it when we was young. Or saw the results of it.
\par I:\tab Did you grow any of your own vegetables or fruit?
\par GB:\tab No, all we had was a back yard. Used to have a few pots on the - tell you what we did - us kids used - did used to do, used to have little - saucers with little bits of
 flannel and grow our own mustard and cress. We used to have them along the - and then if one's got a little bit bigger than the other the other would switch - switch - switch the saucers. Have a couple of sandwiches, it was nice you know.
\par I:\tab Could you keep any livestock, any hens or rabbits or anything like that?
\par GB:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Did you buy any tinned or dried vegetables or fruit?
\par GB:\tab Well no never heard of it. No, never
 heard of it. Always bought - well, you see, in those days - being no refrigeration - sometimes on a Saturday - 'cos you know I'm talking about the days - when the shops used to stop open 'til - Saturday - open 'til about twelve o' clock at night. Well - 
w
hen you went there - you - along there- you could go along and there sometimes with about threepence, they'd - anything they didn't want, they used to call 'em specks and you'd come home with a nice lot of fruit. And you had to cut the bits off that wasn'
t
 any good and you had good fruit you see. You got a fair amount- oh yes, you'd get good value going late at night, you went for your meat. As I say there was not so much refrigeration and you'd go for fish. Or anything. Got it at night when they - especia
l
ly Saturday. They'd got Sunday to get through. And the butchers out there, they would stand with their little straw hats and their striped aprons and they would say, here you are mother, two for the price of one. And you'd get two little joints, and he'd 
say, here you are, pound of sausages for your breakfast. Two bob - half a crown. And the people used to go.
\par I:\tab This was where you used to do most of your shopping?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab How many times a week would you eat meat do you think?
\par GB:\tab Eat meat? Well I suppose we had several types of meat, liver - sausages and then we had just stew with meat in and we had a meat pudding with meat in and a meat pie.
\par I:\tab So you had it more or less every day?
\par GB:\tab So practically, yes, except when - when it was sausages. And of course they were sausages in those days.
\par I:\tab Did you ever buy tinned meat at all?
\par GB:\tab No, never even heard of it.
\par I:\tab Do you remember seeing your mother have less food so that the family could have more?
\par GB:\tab Well I don't know whether she had less
 but I always used to notice that she always used to serve us and - we didn't very often see her eat because - she would be looking after us at table 'cos my father - if my father happened to be there, especially - she - 'cos she had to keep us all under 
c
ontrol so that she couldn't really sit and eat, 'cos although she had the power with one raise of her eyebrows to keep us quiet, 'cos we knew what to expect next, but I've never really seen my mother eat at the table with us because she didn't - whether, 
she did afterwards - well you - you don't know you see, no, you don't know. All you're thinking about is yourself.
\par I:\tab Would your father have anything extra or more or different from the rest of you?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. Oh yes, my father used to have - egg and bacon
 for his breakfast on Sunday morning and then he'd have - nice piece of haddock when he came home for his tea at night and all that sort of thing. Oh yes. My father was a - my father fared very well.
\par I:\tab Would he have breakfast before he went out in the morning?
\par GB:\tab Yes, my mother used to get up half past four - get him off to work. Yes, get him his breakfast at five, yes. He left home at half past five and he cycled to Chelsea.
\par I:\tab Would he always have a cooked breakfast before he went or not?
\par GB:\tab Mostly. Mo
stly a cooked breakfast, yes. 'Cos they were long days - long hours you know. He worked at six - go out at six to work at six and he worked 'til six o'clock at night. And there was no - and there was no five day week, it was Saturdays as well.
\par I:\tab Were you allowed to talk during mealtimes?
\par GB:\tab Well - not really. If - if you did it was low murmuring and that, none of us - and if my father looked up and looked at us like - that that was it. No, we weren't. We were - that was where - children should be seen and
 not heard coming from, I'm sure it was invented in our house.
\par I:\tab Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to have a bit of everything?
\par GB:\tab Well, we only - we didn't have a choice, we had - there was a meat pudding and that was it. And mostly - if it was a bit of sweet it was - rice pudding and it was made with cows milk - not cows milk - with this - goat - yes, tinned.
\par I:\tab What was your parent's attitude if you left some food uneaten on your plate?
\par GB:\tab Well to be quite honest I can never remember any being left. Unless - and that is honest.
\par I:\tab If there was anything on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask for someone to pass it to you or did you have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par GB:\tab Well you just asked for it if you wanted it.
\par I:\tab Could you ask for a second helping?
\par GB:\tab Well we didn't have to ask if there was any left, we were given it you see, but there wasn't always any left you see. Oh yes, my mother did do her utmost to look after us, yes.
\par I:\tab Could you bring toys or books to the table?
\par GB:\tab What's toys? What's toys. Why if we got hold of a comic that someone had give 'em a comic there'd be - there'd be quietness in our house for hours with one comic. And I - do you know - you're not going to bel
ieve this but I never possessed a doll in my life. No. What we used to have my grandma used to make, and children used to all wear black stockings in those days, my grandma used to make us rag dolls out of our old stockings and she used to have little red
 bits for their nose and little red bits for their mouth - that's when - when we were young.
\par I:\tab Little red bits of cloth?
\par GB:\tab Yes. And - yes, and out of old stockings, she used to stuff the stockings. The youngest ones, when we - when we went to work - the younger family got toys, got books and got things, yes.
\par I:\tab With big families the older ones always have it hardest?
\par GB:\tab Yes, that's right. Do you know, I'm not kidding you, I never knew what it was to go out and - when I - I - after I got about six I never
 knew what it was to go out and play, without I had two in a pram and one walking, and I'm holding the pram there by one hand and I'm turning the rope. And when it came to my turn to have a skip nobody would mind the kids so I had to keep turning. I'm not
 
kidding. And of course I never thought no more of it because that - didn't know any different did I? I didn't know any different at all so - I just got on with it. And I suppose in my own way I enjoyed myself you know. Well when you can't know any differe
nt you see you just accept it don't you.
\par I:\tab Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and sit up at table in a certain way?
\par GB:\tab Well we were - we were shown how to use our knives and forks but - my mother never used to make a - issue of it you know, no.
\par I:\tab When could you leave the table?
\par GB:\tab Well mostly - my father was always - the first one to leave the table, you sat until he left and then you - you all leave. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you say grace at meals?
\par GB:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you all sit down at the table for meals together?
\par GB:\tab No. No, because - when we were getting on a little - some of us - the girls went to school, when you've got to take the little - little ones, when there was some very little ones left well you couldn't you see, mum used to get 
us off to school first and then feed the others after. 'Sides, we didn't have enough chairs to go all round.
\par I:\tab Did you always have the same places at the table?
\par GB:\tab No. No special place.
\par I:\tab How was the meal served, did your mother bring the saucepans to the table?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Yes, there was a big board put on the table as you - you were served from the saucepans.
\par I:\tab Did your mother always serve the meal?
\par GB:\tab Well if she was there, yes, if she wasn't well I did.
\par I:\tab What order were people served in?
\par GB:\tab Whoever was there got - served first, that's all there is to it. That's right.
\par I:\tab Where did the younger brothers and sisters sit before they were old enough to feed themselves?
\par GB:\tab Where they used to sit then? In a high chair. Yes, yes, one of the - you know that
 chair that you were saying was a nice chair. Well that type of thing, like that. But it was a hard - wooden - all wooden, with a little hole with a little potty in the middle you know, and a - and a little tray in the front.
\par I:\tab Who fed them?
\par GB:\tab 
Whoever - whoever was there, my mother didn't 'cos she'd got the others to see to, usually myself or my sister, two years younger that had got older you see because she - when she began to get up she also began to help you see, another girl. But of course
 
the boys weren't - they'd do other jobs but they - they didn't have anything to do with like with the children, my eldest brother didn't but he had his little jobs, he had a job of cleaning the windows and things like that you see. But - oh we all had our
 chores, yes.
\par I:\tab Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par GB:\tab Yes. But she - she had rather a bad temper. And she was a prude. Yes. Very prudish my mother. And one day I asked her a question as I was getting on and she - she just smacked me face, and it w
as to do with me - meself and - well she would never tell you anything you see, you had to learn all your - things about anything from other girls. You couldn't - and you know it wasn't - it wasn't really fair. That's why I say -
\par I:\tab I've found this with other people I've talked to that they are often very ignorant about sexual matters?
\par GB:\tab That's right. My - oh you wouldn't dare say anything to - and if - you wouldn't ask a question like that, all in good faith, you couldn't ask a question of my mother. All
 the - all the information that I ever got I got, thank God I had a - a very wonderful grandma. And do you know, perhaps it's not right to say it but I loved my grandma much more than I loved my mother. My grandma was the dearest lady that - to this day I
'
ve never met another lady like her. She used to have the patience of a saint and - she'd - when I was beginning to grow up and I used to visit her, she used to - she'd say to me, come and sit down ducky. Used to go and sit down. Getting a big girl now, sh
e
'd say. Yes. She'd say, well, you know what you've got to do, you've got to be careful you know. And I used to look at her. So she said, you've been talking to the girls? And I used to say, yes. Well, she said, listen. And if there's anything you don't un
d
erstand, I know your mother won't tell you, you come and tell gran. And I used to. I learnt quite a lot from my grandma. She - and - oh she was sweet, she was really lovely, everybody loved her, not only her own family but other people used to come to her
 for advice. She was a sweet lady, really. I was lucky to have a grandma like that.
\par I:\tab One person didn't know what to expect in childbirth even after she was married. No.
\par GB:\tab No. No, that's right,
\par I:\tab The whole thing came as a tremendous shock.
\par GB:\tab Shock, yes.
\par I:\tab As you say it seems very unfair really?
\par GB:\tab Yes. It was. Oh and - even sometimes I - when I went to work - I mean during the - no, just - during the First World War when I was sixteen, that was 1917, I went to work at - making - gas masks for the sol
diers and it was - drummed into me by - real cockney women and I - I was shocked, when I heard 'em sitting there talking and one of them said, look at her with her mouth wide open. I couldn't believe what they said, I couldn't believe it. I could not beli
e
ve 'em. And then that was when I went - I kept thinking about it, thinking about it and I went - I'll go to my grandma. And she knew that - when she saw my face that - there was something wrong. Said, what's the matter love? So I told her. So she says, co
m
e here, sit down, put her arm round me. Now, she said, they've told you in a very bald way, that's wicked she said. Yes. Yes, the baby is born like that. So she said - so then - she - so I said, well how does it get there? You see. So there's my grandma t
e
lling me the difference between a girl and a boy and the way she put it - she ought to have been alive today, she could have taught - she could have taught them how to tell people about sex. Oh - and do you know I thought when she told me and how she expl
a
ined it to me, not like some people think it's dirty, I thought it was wonderful. I did really. And I've never had any - never - I wouldn't let anybody tell anybody - if I hear anybody telling a child, say it's filthy, it's not. I haven't got the sense of
 it but - but my grandma, as I say, she was wonderful. I wish to God she was alive today. Yes.
\par I:\tab Was your mother a very affectionate person?
\par GB:\tab No, not really. She was affectionate to the children - babies when they were born but as they - as they grew older and the next one came along so it - it lessened. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you think this was because she had to work so hard?
\par GB:\tab That's what it was, she couldn't - I mean she didn't - she never had time. I've known her go to bed at night dead in the - and wake up i
n the morning and and she's hardly known how to walk, been so tired. And she couldn't afford to be ill. Oh it was hard in those days, yes. But there again we didn't know did we. So we took it, accepted it you see.
\par I:\tab Did you share any of your worries at all with your mum or not?
\par GB:\tab No, well you couldn't talk to my mother like you could my grandma, my mother was more - oh she didn't want to listen, she hadn't got time - she didn't want to listen and - don't talk to me about things like that, I don't want to
 know. But grandma wasn't like that you see. I got - I think that's why I - I got through life so well as I did because I had the - I'd had the grand advice from my grandma.
\par I:\tab Could you take your worries to your father?
\par GB:\tab Oh - that's unheard of, you wouldn't - well we didn't - we didn't have much conversation ever in our life with our father. No. No.
\par I:\tab Do you think this was general in those days?
\par GB:\tab Lot of it was. Oh a lot of it was, round where we lived it was, yes, the man was the boss.
\par I:\tab He'd just earn the money?
\par GB:\tab That's right. No, that's - no.
\par I:\tab Was he an affectionate man?
\par GB:\tab No. Not at all, no.
\par I:\tab How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par GB:\tab 
Well I don't know - I don't - I don't think there was any expect - what you did - you were there, you did what you were told and if you didn't you got a smack or you got the cane or that sort of thing. You were just - just part of their life and - part of
 their sexual life wasn't it, I mean affection, if - a child was born and that was it you see. You just - you just - lined up.
\par I:\tab Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in any special way?
\par GB:\tab Well - well in a way my mothe
r always used to say when I used to go out with the children, look after the children, take care of 'em. Be careful. Don't talk to anybody, even in those days, don't talk to anybody. All keep together. All that sort of thing she used to tell us. In her wa
y she was trying to give you a warning, yes. What to do.
\par I:\tab Did they say you should hit back or not if another child hurt you?
\par GB:\tab Yes, that was a recognised thing to do that. Don't come and tell me your trouble so that you make it trouble between the parents, fight your own battles, on yes.
\par I:\tab What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par GB:\tab Well - honest, 'cos my parents - I think my parents were honest, clean living, because my mother was - well - my mother always boasted in la
ter life - I had five girls and not one of them brought me home any trouble. That's how she was, and if she threatened us once when she's had us there together when we were getting on, anybody - brings anything home - I'll kill 'em. And we never did. And 
if anything ever tempted us in any way we could hear what - we could hear and see our mother. Yes, and we obeyed. We did obey.
\par I:\tab Was it fairly common for young girls to get in trouble in those days?
\par GB:\tab Well - no, not fairly common. And - and if did it was hidden. There was none of this -
\par I:\tab What did your parents think of swearing?
\par GB:\tab Well - they occasionally swore themselves but - but we were absolutely forbidden. Oh we got - if we swore that was it, oh no. The parents were allowed to do these things but 
not the children, oh no. They would swear, but not these - some of these filthy words you hear now but you know - you hear 'em on television. That's it, that sort of thing, yes.
\par I:\tab When grown-ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par GB:\tab No. No. To be seen and not heard.
\par I:\tab If you did something your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par GB:\tab Well - I can tell you what my mother used to do, she - 'cos she was - got - she could control six of us at the table with a raise of an eyebrow and if the eyebro
w went up the second time, on the wall there used to be a cane with a hook on it. It came down - and you got it. And if you didn't do what you was told then you got a good hiding with the cane. Always had a cane.
\par I:\tab If you were really disobedient you got that?
\par GB:\tab You got it. Yes, you'd get a tanning, a real tanning yes.
\par I:\tab Was it always your mother who gave you a tanning?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, my father - no, as I say my father was a - abstract really to us. He was - he was the man that came in and out to - we just 
saw occasionally. He didn't - really didn't have much to do with us at all. My mother completely controlled all of us.
\par I:\tab He wouldn't punish you?
\par GB:\tab No. I don't - I often wondered - I used to say when I grew up and understood a bit more, I often wondered 
whether we ever belonged to him but - it seemed to be when they used to talk that it was the - in some of the places it was the case of doing this, the man was the boss and then the woman took over after she had the children that was it.
\par I:\tab Can you remember any particular occasion when you were punished?
\par GB:\tab Well, yes, I can it was rather, yes, and it was rather - it was a - rather - really bad once. My - it was caused through my brother - my brother he came - he was in the - I don't know, some - Boys Briga
de or something - and he - and he was the one that should have been punished but my mother went - to go for him with the cane and - two or three days previous I'd been vaccinated, and my mother, went to hit him with the cane and unfortunately it didn't re
a
ch him, it reached me. And I - you know - with a vaccination and it wasn't - I'd got a terrible bad arm there - it wasn't just one, it was three big things. Well my mother - interfered with 'em, you know, and I had to be taken to the doctors and when he s
a
w it he went - off the deep end terrible. But from that - started off eczema. And it went all up me arm, all round - and I lost all me hair. Just through that. Every bit of hair. And then when it did grow it grew curly like this, isn't it funny. Yes, but 
t
hat was bad, and I can still remember it. I'd got two half crowns on my arms and yet - when I - that's what they used to do in those days, and do you know in those days, believe it or not, had a - what would you call him, the Welfare - no, the Medical Off
i
cer you would call him now, well I don't know what they used to call him those days but do you know they used to give money to women for letting them vaccinate their children. Yes. And I was one of them you see. I suppose I was about eight. And oh it was 
a
 terrible arm I had. And I had to wear a bonnet for - I couldn't get to school. I had to wear a bonnet for awful long time. And it was bad, it was really eczema it set off. So you see I can always remember one of the smacks I got. And it wasn't - I didn't
 deserve it. It was my brother you see. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember how you felt about being punished as a child?
\par GB:\tab Well I don't know really, I think we accept - we just sort of accepted it. We'd done - we knew that - well of course my mother was very fair, w
e weren't smacked for nothing. We had done something that annoyed her. 'Course she was very quick tempered but -
\par I:\tab Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from your mother or your father or from both?
\par GB:\tab 
No, I don't think any - any of us were told this sort of thing, it came - I don't know whether it came natural or not but mind you we had - we had those teachers at school and they used to teach us things and what I used to like about it they used to - to
 
try to - teach us how to speak, how to catch 'aitches and how to - all those sort of things. I was very grateful to my - to my teachers for that, but - my - well my father, he never had much conversation with us and my mother was always too busy, she - ne
ver had time - I don't remember mother - either of 'em correcting us in the way we spoke or anything like that, no.
\par I:\tab But the teachers would emphasise that?
\par GB:\tab Oh the teachers were very good. Mind you, they were - they were beauties they were because - th
ey had about - forty to fifty children in their class and they did every lesson, there was no changing, they took you right through the lot. And they were pretty good 'cos I - considering I - I learnt pretty well from them, yes.
\par I:\tab When you had a birthday would it be any different from any other day?
\par GB:\tab No, not at all. Not in any way at all, no. There was no money for - for present and there was no such things as - having anybody in to tea like - oh no.
\par I:\tab You didn't even get a card?
\par GB:\tab No, I can't even remember getting - ever getting cards. Because - well they'd got to be bought and they may have only been a penny a card and a penny for the stamp bits - there it was, money was very short you see.
\par I:\tab Were you even aware it was your birthday?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, we
 knew, oh yes, oh yes, we knew it was our birthday. And sometimes the other children would sort of get paper and try to draw on them. I never forget one - one birthday my youngest one went and put - robins and snow. 'Cos I was born - I was born in March b
ut still it was - Christmas you see. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did you do at Christmas?
\par GB:\tab Well - we used to have a - the Christmases then were not like they are now. We used to have - there was no such thing as a - as presents, you used to have perhaps a - a - she use
d to put - mum used to get so many bright - bright pennies and you see you'd have them put in - in your stocking and you'd have a few nuts and an orange and an apple and perhaps a couple of hankies, pair of stockings and the boys used to have socks. That 
was your Christmas. There were no - no - there was no such thing as presents, they couldn't afford them, not gifts as they give it now. No.
\par I:\tab Do you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par GB:\tab No, not when I was very young. Not - not when I was - a young
 - very young child but when my sisters - we was just gone like fourteen or fifteen - then my mother got a piano and the youngest were able to learn to play. But - not me. No. No. I would have loved to have played.
\par I:\tab Was there anyone in the family who sang, did you ever make music together as a family?
\par GB:\tab Oh - I used to sing when I was young. I joined a - I joined a choir - I joined a choir and I - I could - I had a very - high voice but soft, you know, not a - not very powerful, I wouldn't have done anyt
hing with it, but I liked it. But there again, being the eldest of a large family - it was - you can't go tonight we're going out. So after about three months I lost it. And I used to love it. Well - well as a matter of fact you talking about that - last 
w
eek - before you came, at the club they were doing a - recording for - something for Christmas or something and they asked me if I could - if I would sing on it. And I did sing. I haven't heard it back yet. But they said it was very - it was very nice and
 I want to keep in. But I haven't heard it yet. But that's the only time that I've - we've had a - to be able to sing. But - I enjoyed it.
\par I:\tab Did your parents play any games with you? Anything like Ludo or things like that?
\par GB:\tab No, we didn't - we didn't have Ludo. No, I don't know what other families did but in our family nothing - was nothing like that, no. No.
\par I:\tab How about books in the house?
\par GB:\tab Well we didn't have books in the house but the two of us, my eldest brother and I, we used to belong to the lib
rary. We used the Chase library an awful lot. 'Cos I'm - I'm fond to this day - I've got books over there - I'm fond of this day reading. I love reading.
\par I:\tab How about magazines or newspapers?
\par GB:\tab Well you could - they were only ha'penny each, you could - yes, my father always had an evening paper. And on the Sunday course the old - 'News of the World' was - yes, just the same, yes.
\par I:\tab Which evening paper did you have?
\par GB:\tab My father used to - yes - 'The Star'.
\par I:\tab Did your mother or father read very much?
\par GB:\tab Well my father only read the paper for the - football and all that sort of thing but - my mother used to pick it up to read but it was my eldest brother and I that used to devour the paper.
\par I:\tab Do you remember a funeral in the family before 1918? Do you remember going to a funeral before 1918?
\par GB:\tab No. Not before 1918. 1920 but 1918, no.
\par I:\tab Were people still all in black and this sort of thing for mourning clothes?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, everybody - and the poorer you were the more expensive 
funeral you had with all the crepe and the horses all decorated and - and you had to be in the mourning for a year and all that - oh - I think it was awful now but that was the - that was the thing they did in those days. You know, the horses with those b
ig things on their heads. Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Were you taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relatives very much?
\par GB:\tab Oh we used to - oh our family - our family was very close, auntie's and uncles, oh yes, oh yes, we - we saw an awful lot of them. Not so much ne
ighbours 'cos we'd got plenty of - relatives you see. Oh yes, we saw them, and we never broke up until - seeing them such a lot until we all got married. Oh we were very close, play with our cousins, go out with our cousins.
\par I:\tab Were you taken out shopping at all with your parents?
\par GB:\tab Never been shopping with either of 'em in me life I don't think, no, oh my father, no. My - my father - what - no my father was just a stranger that lived in the house to me.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go out with him at all?
\par GB:\tab Well - 
I'll tell you when we did, when I got older - we - I can remember him - my mother - him taking my mother and me to the - my mother and I - I suppose I should say - to the - Holborn Empire. And you're not going to believe this, but when - while we were out
side he held out his hand for the money for me to go in. I was working mind, yes. My father gave you nothing.
\par I:\tab This would be soon after you started work?
\par GB:\tab Oh - yes, my - yes, well I was only about fourteen 'cos I started work when I was thirteen you see, oh but my father - my father didn't give anything. My mum did but not my father.
\par I:\tab Do you remember any other outings with your parents, what did you do on Bank Holidays?
\par GB:\tab Well, my - we didn't go with my father but my - when my father was at - I told
 you he was a wheelwright - well at the time I'm talking about now he worked on the railway, see, for the railway, making the wheels just the same, and - he used to get privilege tickets, so we - mum used to take us. 'Cos in those days you could get with 
a privilege ticket for a child you could get of - Southend and back for sixpence ha'penny you see. Oh yes, mum used to have these tickets you see, and take us.
\par I:\tab This was while you were still at school?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par GB:\tab No. No. Not when I was a child. Not when I was young, no.
\par I:\tab How did you spend your Saturdays in those days?
\par GB:\tab Well - what we used to do on a Saturday was when we used to try to earn little money, we used to go shopping for other people. And in those d
ays, in the winter in those days in winter you know you could buy coal by seven pounds. And we used to - we had a - in the winter we had a little regular clientele with a little pushchair to go and get seven pounds of coal or fourteen pounds of coals for 
people, and you'd get perhaps a farthing or ha'penny for getting it you see. Those sort of things. Go shopping, you see. And even go to the pawnshop for 'em to get their parcels out of pawn you know. 'Cos there was awful lot of that in those days.
\par I:\tab So Saturday you'd be earning yourself some money?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Yes, our pocket money.
\par I:\tab How about Sunday?
\par GB:\tab Well Sunday morning like I told you before Sunday morning we had to stay in bed 'til my father was - got - then we had our breakfast. Well then we used to 
take the - the young ones, we used to push them in the pram and take them out. And - then in Sunday afternoon we used to go to Sunday school and had our dinner then we came home. And then of course it was Sunday evenings was - mum and - perhaps dad might 
take mum out with him and of course we all sat in with the children, the younger ones you see.
\par I:\tab Did your parents think it wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par GB:\tab Oh no. Sunday was just another day of the week. Oh no.
\par I:\tab Did they go to place of worship or not?
\par GB:\tab I can't ever remember them, no.
\par I:\tab Do you know what denomination they would call themselves?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, we were - Church of England. Yes.
\par I:\tab You used to go to Church of England did you?
\par GB:\tab Yes, that's right.
\par I:\tab Were there any Sunday school outings?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, that's what we lived for wasn't it. You made - made sure you went to Sunday school every Sunday afternoon so you got your little star on your card so then you got your ticket to go on the outing, if you di
dn't have a certain amount of stars you never went on the outing, without paying, otherwise you went free you see, oh yes. We were - I never forget, we went - once we went on a - what do you call it - brake with all the fringe on top you know. Rushted Woo
ds. Oh it was gorgeous. The horses in front and driver with a lovely whip.
\par I:\tab Where did you usually go on these Sunday school outings?
\par GB:\tab Well that one - one was Ashstead Woods and then - most - there weren't many of those types but we went once to - when 
I was very young we went once by train to Worthing. And I've never been there since but I still remember what I saw there. I was only about eight I suppose, eight or nine. We went to Worthing and we had a lot of - voluntary workers with us 'cos you know -
 the trains then were just the ordinary - little compartments with eight in a compartment, so there had to be quite a few people going because, even then, in those days, we weren't all that good. We had to be looked after, yes.
\par I:\tab The trains used to get wrecked a bit did they?
\par GB:\tab Well - no, no. No, we were not that. No, I don't - no, I won't have that because we weren't - what - what do you call it - smash anything up, no, no, not vandals, we were not, we were - we used to - we would drop the windows down a
nd - you know - and all that sort of thing and climb underneath the seats and all that, but no, we - were not - we were not destructive. No. Oh - another thing we were afraid of - and - many's the time we've looked up at that chain and loved to pull it, b
ut not one of us ever did. We - oh I don't know what they'd have done to us, I don't really.
\par I:\tab Were there any other social activities organised by the church that you took part in?
\par GB:\tab Well we used to go to a - a Band of Hope, you know, on a - on a - eveni
ng, an evening, used to go to the Band of Hope and they used to have a - used to have little hymns to start off and then there used to be all sorts of little things what I suppose you would call today a kind of a - well of course they have them now - club
, you know a - for - and it used to be boys and girls together. They used to have skip - they used to have the big halls, they used have skipping ropes, you'd skip and - all that sort of thing you see.
\par I:\tab More or less the equivalent of a youth club?
\par GB:\tab That - yes that's it, that's word I couldn't remember - yes, youth club.
\par I:\tab Was it the church choir you belonged to for a while?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Yes, it was a - St Marys - somewhere in the Borough, I don't know if it's there now but - in the Borough of London, you know, in the Borough there, near London Bridge - used to go. 'Course it's a long time ago but - I did used to enjoy that.

\par I:\tab So you used to go to church as well as Sunday school did you?
\par GB:\tab Well, no, I didn't used to go to this church, I used to go to the 
choir because that was the only choir that we knew. Our church didn't run a choir. And it was of an evening you see that we used to go, we used to go two evenings a week. And we used to - and the - the songs that we used to sing were not hymns, it was cla
ssically, like 'Where my Caravan has Rested', all that type of - classics. It - no, no, it was all classic you see.
\par I:\tab Did you have any outings or anything with them?
\par GB:\tab No, I didn't go - I - tell you the truth I didn't belong to it long enough because I - 'cos every time I went anywhere I had stay home in the finish and mind the babies.
\par I:\tab Do you remember the church running any temperance club?
\par GB:\tab Oh what did they used to call that? What when you signed the pledge? Oh - oh yes, they used to have the one t
hat I used to go - at the end of our road used to have one - one of those, yes, that's - we went - 'cos that's where I belonged to the Sunday school. Oh yes, you signed - we signed the pledge when we was very young.
\par I:\tab Did they have any special social activities or not?
\par GB:\tab Well I can't recall, not - all of 'em.
\par I:\tab Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par GB:\tab Yes, through school. Through school, not through home, through school. Teacher were very good in those day you kn
ow. Yes, they used to teach us, they used to - we didn't have a thing called a morning assembly like they have now, we used to have - and the teacher used to - and where they were having a - assembly then we had - a - spelling lessons in the morning while
 the teacher's doing all theirs, spelling lessons you see and - then we used to - but we did have scriptures. We had scripture.
\par I:\tab Did you ever have family prayers at home?
\par GB:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Did your father take an interest in politics ?
\par GB:\tab Yes, my father was
 in those days known as a Radical. And he was a real right Radical too, I'll tell you, yes. 'Cos my father lost his job at - Tillings through a - the men - through - through sticking up so long - so much for his men, getting with the unions, yes, he got -
 yes, he lost his job, when they discharged the men they discharged him as well, oh he was a real right Labour well later years he was a Labour - Labour man. Oh he was - was a shocking heckler. Oh. Terrible.
\par I:\tab Do you remember if he ever told you about his views or why he held them, do you know what made him such a Radical?
\par GB:\tab No, I don't know really 'cos he'd had rather a good bringing up, he'd been at college and all that sort of thing, but of course his parents weren't badly off, but - I don't know but h
e was a real - it was - because he used to belong to what they called a Radical club, and he was one of the officials there, I mean, he - he was really - up in it. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you know whether he was a member of a party?
\par GB:\tab Well I don't know - I 
don't know whether you would call it a member of the party' or not but I know that he was always - when they went - 'cos - before Labour came in 'cos he was always like Liberal, 'cos there was no Labour then, but this Radical business was coming on a long
 time before that, and I can remember 'cos we used to - we used to go to Christmas parties that were run by the Radical people you see.
\par I:\tab He used to work for the Liberals at election time?
\par GB:\tab Yes, I suppose - yes. Oh yes, we always had to wear - oh - we c
ouldn't have any other colour, we had to wear blue. Else we'd get into trouble. And he used to - blue was the Liberal colour? Yes. And he used to - yes, and my - my father used to have the bills up in the window and all that sort of thing, yes.
\par I:\tab You told me he was sacked because of his union activities - were his politics involved with that at all?
\par GB:\tab Well I don't know, he worked for the - he worked for the railway you see, so I don't know - 'course it was a - I don't know - I cannot remember whether the
 N.U.R, was in - in vogue then or not but I know that - when I worked on the railway - I was - I was in the N.U.R, you see.
\par I:\tab Do you remember your mother voting at all before 1919?
\par GB:\tab No. My mother never bothered to vote at all. No, not even when they got the - you know, they fought for the vote and all that, and never went - no, she, never at time, she always said she'd never got time.
\par I:\tab Do you know what her views were, whether she had any?
\par GB:\tab Not really.
\par I:\tab When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their time, you told me your father liked his glass of beer?
\par GB:\tab He's all - he lived there. My father. And my mother just - stayed in with us - he might - and it was a local just at the top and he might send down - my father went every n
ight of his life when he was well. He never missed. And he used to come home dirty, wash and dress up like a single man and go to the local, and there he'd stop in saloon bar all night 'til they closed. That's, that was his life. He was like - just like a
 single man.
\par I:\tab You say he would occasionally take your mother out on a Sunday, would this still be to the local?
\par GB:\tab Yes, only out like - anywhere like that you see, oh yes, it wouldn't be anything else. No. Oh my father was a very selfish man.
\par I:\tab You say he used to like cycling?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, he used to go out - I'll tell you when he used to do that, he used to go out on Sunday mornings with his brother, he'd got a brother that was very - keen cyclist too. They used to cycle out to dinner out as far as Farnb
orough and all that sort of thing and then be back home in time for dinner. That's in the summer of course. In the winter he used to like his bed. Stop in bed.
\par I:\tab Did your mother ever go out to enjoy herself apart from these evenings with your father?
\par GB:\tab 
Oh she used to go out - she used to belong to a - a mothers meeting and then she used to go out sometimes if my father was - working late or anything like - you know, she'd go - go out with her sisters, you know, they used to go - perhaps one sister used 
to go with the other one and both visit somebody else. That sort of way of going on.
\par I:\tab Your father used to get home about six thirty did he?
\par GB:\tab Yes, somewhere - he used to leave home about - he used to have to be at work at six o'clock in the morning and he used to get home I suppose about half past six 'cos he used to cycle you see.
\par I:\tab Did your father take part in any other sport except cycling?
\par GB:\tab Well when he was a very young man he used to box - he was a - a - amateur boxer.
\par I:\tab He didn't keep that up after he was married?
\par GB:\tab No. But he did - he did used to win prizes when he was young.
\par I:\tab Did he attend the races or have a bet or anything like that?
\par GB:\tab No. Not that I can remember, no, I don't think he did, I - I think he wouldn't spend it on that, he wanted to spend it on beer.
\par I:\tab Did your father or mother belonged to savings clubs?
\par GB:\tab Oh no, we used to pay - they used to save - my mother used to belong to a loan club that you had a - you know, at - draw out money at Christmas and then if you - you could borrow off it, pay back, that sort of thing. Oh yes, they belonged to that.

\par I:\tab Were these called slate clubs?
\par GB:\tab Slate club, that's right. I think nearly everybody did in those days. Save a bit of money for Christmas you see.
\par I:\tab How did you get on with your brothers and sisters, was there any one you felt particularly close to?
\par GB:\tab Well - well I got on all right with all of them, of course you have chips up lik
e that but I mean to say - and we're very close too now but - the one that - 'course you see I'm a lot older than - my youngest sister, she - she's - I'm ten years older than her. Now she's my favourite sister and I think I am hers because - she never - I
 never go one week without she does not, up here to see if I'm all right. But when I was a - when I was younger and the eldest of - I seemed to be apart because the others being younger I always used to see - seem to be mother not sister, you see.
\par I:\tab As a child who did you play with, your neighbours or your brothers and sisters?
\par GB:\tab Well - we all - well, you didn't play - I didn't play with brothers and sisters 'cos there wasn't any my - you know, they were dropping down, but I used to have to mind the children, but yes, we used to play with the neighbours.
\par I:\tab Where did you play usually?
\par GB:\tab In the street. Well there was no - parks where I lived, no.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go in other children's homes to play?
\par GB:\tab Well sometimes used to go in their garden. 'Cos along where we were we had different gardens where you could get from one into the other out of your own so you used to go in that way you see.
\par I:\tab What sort of games did you play?
\par GB:\tab Well one of my favourite, don't see it now, we used to call it - alleygobs in them days, it was a ball and four stones. And you play on - sit on the floor and play on the asphalt.
\par I:\tab Fivestones?
\par GB:\tab Yes, Well they used to get - in my days - in my days we didn't call 'em fivestones, no, they called 'em alleygobs. Yes, that was one 
of my favourites. Then course there was - you always got - you could always get hold of a piece of cash cord - sash cord to make a skipping rope. Then we used to have - hoops. The boys had a iron one with a - with a hook thing they used to call a skimmer,
 and we used to have a wooden hope with a stick. They used to be sold for about 'threepence.
\par I:\tab Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par GB:\tab Yes, my mother - well we got - dirty, couldn't help it. But - of course when I was old - then I was old enough
 to wash the others you see so - my mum never had any worry about that sort of thing, 'cos - 'cos if we saw they were getting a little bit too dirty we'd - dash 'em in and wash 'em before mum come in you see. 'Cos mum was at work most of the time you see.

\par I:\tab Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab They didn't discourage you from playing with certain children?
\par GB:\tab Oh no, we mixed - we made good mixers too.
\par I:\tab Did you belong to any youth organisations other than those you've mentioned with the church?
\par GB:\tab No.
\par I:\tab How did you spend your free time when you were at school, did you have any hobbies, did you collect things or have pets?
\par GB:\tab Well as I told you I'm very fond of reading, and I used to - and then - my favourite - was Friday af
ternoons when we used to - we were taught to knit socks and we had a girl there that could - could read beautifully, and she used - we all were knitting, she would sit and read to us. Oh I used to love that the best of all. That was beautiful that was. Bu
t
 of course mind the teachers used to try to make - to make us happy but they had as much as they could do with teachings and then to see that - if we got wet feet they got them dry because no end of children had - some no shoes and some poorly clad you kn
ow. They had their - they talk about what the teachers do now with the dinners but they want to see what the teachers did then. Yes. They were good those teachers they were. I hated it when I had to leave school.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go out cycling as a child or walking or fishing or anything?
\par GB:\tab No, we used to go - no - me, I can't ride a bike, only went once, fell off, never been on one since, but - we used to go - no, we used to - when we - when it was holidays, you know, the summer holidays, we - my mother u
sed to pack us up sandwiches and a - and a bottle of water and a bottle of cold tea and all that and two or three coppers and we used to go right up to the park where they'd got swings, used to take us sometimes an hour to walk there. And - we'd stay ther
e all day and then come home and then mum would have a - when she came in from work she'd cook us a meal at home, 'cos while she was doing that we'd be bashing the other ones, getting them - we'd keep them all day long out in the park.
\par I:\tab Would this be one of the big main parks?
\par GB:\tab Yes, the park I'm talking about now is Southwark Park, there's still a Southwark Park there now, but what it's like I wouldn't know now.
\par I:\tab Did your take part in any sports as a girl?
\par GB:\tab Yes, I used to run. You know, with a - with a school - school - yes, used to run.
\par I:\tab How about cinemas or theatres while you were still at school?
\par GB:\tab Well didn't have much to do with theatres but of course I can - of course I can remember the - the penny pictures when you used to go in - the mov
ing pictures but of course silent. And - I can - I can remember those. And I used to like the pictures - 'cos I'm very - rather - rather partial to the cinema now. I like the cinema. Yes. Yes, I like the cinema.
\par I:\tab How about music halls or concerts while you were still at school?
\par GB:\tab Oh we went - oh I don't know about still at school but when I was just left school we used to go to - two or three of us used to get together and go in the - you in the gallery, and it - and - that same time we used to go in th
e - what used to be the old -
\par I:\tab Did your parents give you any regular pocket money?
\par GB:\tab No, none at all. None at all. They couldn't afford it. Well my father could have done but he wanted it for his beer didn't he, so - no.
\par I:\tab Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after the house or family?
\par GB:\tab No. No. Only us, that's all, only the children.
\par I:\tab How did you manage when your mother was ill or confined to bed with the children?
\par GB:\tab Well the situation again is as I told you the other day, if a w
oman was ill - she had - things called neighbours, like I told you, they would came in and take the children away, they would attend to the woman - because everybody did it for everybody else. The spirit of comradeship in those days was marvellous.
\par I:\tab So when your mother was having another baby the neighbours would help?
\par GB:\tab That's right. Yes. Oh yes. One would come and take the children, another one take the washing, another one'd stop with the nurse while mum was - never any bother in that, and you daren'
t mention money to them, if you did that was an insult. They didn't want paying. You did it - they did it for you, you did if for them.
\par I:\tab You say you had plenty of relatives living near by?
\par GB:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Where did you see them as a rule?
\par GB:\tab Either home - well mostly - going to visit them, they never visited us very much. Going to visit them.
\par I:\tab Were these your father's people?
\par GB:\tab No. None of my father's at all, all my mother's. My father's people lived in Manchester and we never saw much of them at all.
\par I:\tab Where did your parents see their friends?
\par GB:\tab Well usual place, in the pub.
\par I:\tab Did your mother have any friends of her own that used to come round?
\par GB:\tab No, because she had two sisters living just round the corner and that was - they were who she made the friends you see.
\par I:\tab Were friends invited into the home at all?
\par GB:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Would neighbours call in casually with out any invitation?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. Yes, 'cos you see in those days the door stood open, and then they'd call down and - whoever - mum say 
who is it? And say, come on down. Oh mum made - if mum was home and that made them a cup of tea and make them welcome like they did, in the old days everybody did that, 'cos all these - in those days - all these - these doors would be standing open, not c
losed like that. Oh no.
\par I:\tab Your parents used to go visiting relatives, did they go visiting friends and neighbours?
\par GB:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab People often tell us that in those days people made their own amusements, what did your parents used to do when they got together with their relatives or friends?
\par GB:\tab Well we - well we didn't have a piano when we were at my age, but we had relatives that did so they used to - 'specially Saturday nights - there used to be - get - take the beer in and get round the piano and - and 
they'd be singing the - and someone'd be - could always find someone that could play the piano, always in those days because a lot of them were taught, 'cos we've got some elderly people now that can play it beautiful where we are, and they used to make -
 and round the piano and men used to sing all the old songs and - and then there used to be - sandwiches and - and beetroot and all that stuff all landed round, it had to be - you had to make your own enjoyment 'cos there was nothing else.
\par I:\tab Apart from singsongs round the piano were there any games?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, used to play cards, oh yes. Play cards, you know, I don't know - understand much about cards but they used to gamble with - ha'pennies in those days, yes. Play cards, you know, I don't know
\par I:\tab Many people divide society into different social classes, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people as belonging to one and some to another?
\par GB:\tab Yes, only - the rich and the poor. That's all. That was with division made, no difference between - there was just the rich and the poor.
\par I:\tab And you belonged to the poor?
\par GB:\tab We belonged to the poor. Even a shopkeeper that had got a good going concern would - was rich to us you see, he was rich you see, the other people we never knew anything about at all, no
t - lords and ladies, nothing like that, no. Just the rich and the poor, no, weren't even aware of them, no.
\par I:\tab What other sort of occupations would you consider poor?
\par GB:\tab Well mostly the labouring people were poor and them that earned their living by labo
uring you see. And - well there was quite a lot of road sweepers and all that sort that the money wasn't much in those days. But now - people that had good jobs in those days are what you - people look down on now, well bus conductors, bus drivers, police
men, postmen, in my day they were - they were - comfortably off in our day, that's what we thought, we didn't know but - 'cos they'd got a uniformed job and they'd got the uniform with their job they were well off. Yes.
\par I:\tab And they had regular money too?
\par GB:\tab That's right, they never - and providing they looked after the job they never came out of work you see.
\par I:\tab Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently form people of another?
\par GB:\tab No. No. No.
\par I:\tab Were yon ever told to curtsey or anything like this to anyone?
\par GB:\tab No, we - but we always taught - like when we've been out with my mum, if we got on a bus and we were sitting and an elderly person was standing we were all taught to stand - to stand up and give the lady or gentleman 
a seat. Always, my mother wouldn't have it - that we sat.
\par I:\tab Were you ever taught to call people sir or madam?
\par GB:\tab No.
\par I:\tab In the district who were considered the most important people where you lived?
\par GB:\tab Well I don't know, the doctor I think. The doctor I think was the most important person.
\par I:\tab How about teachers of clergymen, these sort of people?
\par GB:\tab Well - of course - oh well, of course the clergyman - the - course we had a Canon at our church, we were St Marks and he was a Canon Veasey but the - 'cours
e mind you the teachers were good, I'm not going to kid you, you see - they were good the teachers. I know they were good to us and they taught me - and of course I wanted to learn I used to get little extra tuition you know, used to stay behind and - and
 she - they used to give me - well they didn't used - they call them essays I think now but we used to call it composition, they used to give me that to do and they did try to get me on well, 'cos that's how I passed that scholarship you see.
\par I:\tab Would you put the teachers in the rich or poor class?
\par GB:\tab Oh - well rich. Oh definitely, and they were greatly respected in those days too. A teacher was somebody. Yes.
\par I:\tab Who do you think these people associated with in their free time?
\par GB:\tab You mean the teachers? Well I never - I never thought about it but I should imagine their own teachers and that type of - you know - people that they knew that - that taught, they were awfully nice I know that.
\par I:\tab What sort of people would you say went to church in those days?
\par GB:\tab Well I don't - I don't know many people - anybody round where I lived that went with the grown ups that went to church, it was all the children.
\par I:\tab It was just the children used to go?
\par GB:\tab Well now they were sent to Sunday school not to teach them religion, to get rid of them, so they could have a sleep. You know. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you notice any difference in chapel people or was this about the same?
\par GB:\tab Well - yes, I did, because I had an - one of my aunts, she was a Baptist and I noticed a difference in the -
 the - they were more friendly than the Church of England. When you went into their place they welcomed you. But when you go into the Church of England they don't even welcome you now, so that's what I liked about them, yes. And then when you came out the
y
 shook hands with you and - and said they hoped they'd see you again. You see that? Yes, I liked that better than ours - the Church of England. I would - I say I'm Church of England because I was christened in a Church of England but - to be quite honest 
I really prefer the chapels. The free churches.
\par I:\tab Where you lived as a child did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or would there be different groups, you mentioned the postmen and this sort of thing, can you think of any others?
\par GB:\tab In which way do you mean live. Do you mean the way - what food they had and all that sort of thing?
\par I:\tab Were some families thought of as rough and some as respectable?
\par GB:\tab Oh you got - oh, yes, you got your - you got your nuisances, yes, where 
they used to row and - have fights and all that, yes. There were - we used to have a particular one, the name of Tamplin, they used to have fight - boxes up - fights every Saturday night, they used to - oh the police used to come down every Saturday night
.
 Yes. Yes, they were - but the - well the - the men used to like it 'cos they used to think it was fun, you know, the other men but - used to be jolly noisy, but they didn't half used to beat one another up they did. Only their own family mind, nobody els
e.
\par I:\tab What were the main distinctions between rough families and respectable families?
\par GB:\tab Well - if you find a one that was very respectful they - they - they didn't mix with
 the other people much, they - would pass the time of day but they wouldn't mix with other people you see, you - we had one across the way to us, they - he owned a - a couple of traps and he used to let them out and all sort of thing and of course he got 
- plenty of money, well he - that family wouldn't have any - didn't have anything to do with any of us, kept entirely by themselves. They didn't have - right opposite where I used to live.
\par I:\tab How about their children?
\par GB:\tab Well they didn't have any children, they didn't, you see, yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember any distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers?
\par GB:\tab No, not really.
\par I:\tab Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different social classes?
\par GB:\tab Well if you call it social clas
ses, my father used the saloon bar where the others all used the public, there's your social difference. Though I don't say he could afford it but he did, you see, yes, so - that's a little bit of the difference you see. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You think he thought himself a little different?
\par GB:\tab Well of course I suppose because he was a craftsman, 'cos he - mind he was very clever. He's - went in for a competition once with one of his wheels and he got a marvellous - we used to have it - a small one it was like that,
 beautifully made, used to have it on the wall as an ornament, a beautiful thing. He was clever, Well of course he'd served his apprenticeship and everything, went right through it you see, that's why.
\par I:\tab You think he felt this?
\par GB:\tab Yes, just a little bit,
 yes, just a little bit, yes. 'Cos he never went - I must admit he never went out at night with a scarf round his neck, my father always wore a collar tie, and he always went round properly dressed, not any how. Always. Very proud of his appearance.

\par I:\tab Do you - think your mother saw herself as belonging to any particular social class?
\par GB:\tab Well I don't know 'cos she was a - she was pretty well brought up, my mother was at - but I don't know whether - I can't remember whether she did that 'cos of course she h
ad to work so hard all her life you see. I mean I was only a small child and I can remember her at - on her hands and knees scrubbing somebody else's floor to make money.
\par I:\tab Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another do you think?
\par GB:\tab Well I think so if you got - but it had - you had to get money, you had to get a better job. Yes, you could - of course it wasn't called keeping up with the Jones' then but there was a similar sort of thing like that going on.
\par I:\tab Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par GB:\tab No, not a real - not real gentleman and real lady but nature's lady and nature's gentleman. Yes.
\par I:\tab What would this mean?
\par GB:\tab Well the man that used to be called that was a - was a - he used to treat ever
ybody with greatest respect. And he would always - touch his forelock like that if you saw him and he was a nice man, he was. But I don't know about a lady but this man was a very nice man. And he - he was a bachelor and he lived with his mum and I suppos
e maybe being with his mum it taught - was like that, but he was a nice man.
\par I:\tab This was more his character than his wealth or anything like that?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, he didn't have - they didn't have money, no, that's why they called him nature's gentleman, it wasn't money that made him a gentleman it was just - born in him I suppose. Was a nice man.
\par I:\tab Do you remember seeing the police around where you lived as a child?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, used to see them. But course in those days they were - what I term policeman, they 
were big bonny men you know, with big moustaches you know and - and they used - and you know, they - they didn't have any trouble with the children 'cos they - what they used to do if they did - the kids did anything wrong and they see 'em, the policeman 
w
ould have his - he had - they used to have - woollen gloves then and the police - they'd flick his gloves round his ears and say, I want no more of that, off home, don't let me catch you again. And they didn't. They used to obey the policeman. Oh they - t
hey did - they were really - and you know you could never frighten a child by turning round and telling a policeman 'cos policeman was friend of all the children. Oh yes.
\par I:\tab How do you think the police treated people?
\par GB:\tab Well - there were - unless they wer
e really bad there wasn't all this lot of arrest going on, there was - if a man - got drunk and he got a - you know - nuisance then they would arrest them, but otherwise they'd get rid of him, send him home. Or - like my father got like that a couple of t
imes and they used to, know where he lived, send round to my mother, my mother used to come down and take him home, they didn't used to do all this - putting them in jail you know. No.
\par I:\tab So you feel they were pretty fair?
\par GB:\tab Oh 
they were good. Yes. But I don't know why, when I look at the policemen now I can't believe it you know because they - to me in my young days, it may be just that I was little, they always used to be big broad - broad men with nice moustaches and - oh lov
ely they used to be. Used to go up and slip your hands in theirs you know and - they'd look down at you and they'd hold your hand and - oh yes, they were lovely. And they all pound the beat, they all walked.
\par I:\tab Was your home rented?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Did you see anything of the landlord?
\par GB:\tab No. It was an agent that used to come.
\par I:\tab What did you feel about him as a landlord?
\par GB:\tab Never even thought about him, I knew we had to pay to live there you see.
\par I:\tab Do you remember as a child feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par GB:\tab Well not when I was very young but after when I got - before I was ten years of age I knew they had to struggle. Yes.
\par I:\tab How did you feel about this as a child?
\par GB:\tab Well - you didn't know any different did you. I know we 
used to have to go - here in the mornings and get up early in the mornings and go and get the cheap meat and the - you know, and the - loaves of bread so that they could - the money would stretch. But there again we didn't know any different so we all qui
te happy about it.
\par I:\tab What difference did it make to the family when your father was ill or out of work?
\par GB:\tab Well I can't remember my father ever being out of work, but when he was ill - that made a difference because in those days they didn't pay for sickn
ess. They never had holidays 'cos they didn't pay for holidays either. So when you had a holiday when you - they used to hate the Easter holidays because they had their boxing - they had - let me see - Good Friday they were without pay, Saturday if they s
topped out without pay and then Monday. So you see it make a short money a week for money.
\par I:\tab So holidays weren't all that popular?
\par GB:\tab No. No, no, no. No such things as a week's holiday, fortnight's holiday like they get with pay not now, now. There again we never knew any different so -
\par I:\tab Did you ever get any help from the guardians or the parish or any charity?
\par GB:\tab No. No, no. No, no, they got - my parents - didn't - do that. They - they worked, at least my mother did.
\par I:\tab When there was someone in the district people disapproved of very strongly was there any way in which they showed it?
\par GB:\tab If they did they always did it with the parents but never the children. We were never allowed to - boycott the children. No, that was the parents at fault, 'cos there
 were - used to get some that - used to beat his - beat their wives. Well in those days it was a - well some of the women thought - thought there was something wrong with their husbands if they didn't get beaten in the old days, I'll tell you that. Well t
here - I heard a young woman not so very long ago, up in the north, she said, well if I did that my husband's got the right to thump me. And she wasn't thirty. I'd have thumped them.
\par I:\tab But they didn't actually have rough music?
\par GB:\tab No, never had anything like that, no. I have heard of that but I - don't remember ever hearing it, no.
\par I:\tab Were you ever given any lessons by one of your parents before you went to school?
\par GB:\tab No. Nothing. I went to school at three. Yes. Yes they did, oh yes, they and the didn't c
all it - they didn't call it kindergarten or nursery school either, as it was the - lowest school in infants when you used to - we used to play with bricks and learn the a-b-c, and the 1-2,3 and all that, we used to learn a little sum about a-b-c. Oh yes.

\par I:\tab Did you go for the whole day straight away, or was this a half day, just mornings, at three?
\par GB:\tab Well as far as I can remember we went - we went at nine o'clock in the morning and come home at twelve and - then we went from two 'til four. More an ordina
ry day, yes. Only in the afternoon we used to be put - put on little palias things on the floor to have a sleep. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of school was this, was this a church school?
\par GB:\tab Oh no, it was the - used to be called then the School Board for London.
\par I:\tab Was this a mixed school, girls and boys?
\par GB:\tab There was - in the infants they were mixed, but when you got to a certain age, I don't know exactly what the age was, I cannot remember quite that but - the girls went into the girls school on the next floor, th
e infants on the first - on the ground floor, the girls on the first floor and the boys on the top. And, that's where you were segregated, I forget exactly which age it was that we - we were young.
\par I:\tab Did you go to any other school apart from this one?
\par GB:\tab 
Well the only one - this one I can remember - one - the one I can remember most of course is the one that - the Malbury Road school that I went all those years but - of course I didn't go to kinder - that kindergarten thing then, that was at Gloucester Ro
ad school you see. And from there, when we moved away, then - then I went to Malbury Road school and continued me education they you see. The one school, yes.
\par I:\tab That was the London School Board too?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, it's got it still - I think it's still there now, I think it's still got the L.B.S on it.
\par I:\tab How did you get to school?
\par GB:\tab Walked.
\par I:\tab How long did it take, was it far away?
\par GB:\tab Well no - not really, let me see - as far as from - from here to the other side of Camberwell Green.
\par I:\tab Just about five minutes?
\par GB:\tab Well something like that, yes. Only we had to cross a - we had to cross Old Kent Road and it - even in those days the - traffic was pretty bad with the horse and carts and all that but - of course we had no escorts across the road, no lollipop m
en or anything liked that. No.
\par I:\tab Did anyone used to go to school with you?
\par GB:\tab Well we used to take - well, my sister used to go next to me you see, 'course I - it was - as I say, I was older than three when I went to that school, I was in the infants - higher in the infants you see.
\par I:\tab Where did you have your midday meal?
\par GB:\tab Oh came home always. Oh yes. But it was only the charity children that had the bowls of soup and bread free. Well not charity children but the very poor.
\par I:\tab You told me you liked school?
\par GB:\tab Oh I loved it. Do you know - if I - I'm too old really to go back now if I could find somewhere to take me, I'd love to go to school. I loved it, I like to know things, I want to know things you see. I do an awful lot of - crossword puzzles now so
 that I can still continue - and I won a quiz the other day at the centre, because I'd a good - fair - of what do you call it - common sense or - I don't know, just that - I won a quiz. Yes. Yes. Yes. But crosswords help you quite a lot.
\par I:\tab How did you feel about your teachers at this school?
\par GB:\tab Oh I liked 'em all. I loved my teachers, yes, because - I used to do - 'cos I was brought up - I had to do what I was told - I was told - I did what I was told with the teacher and 'course - several - several times
 I became what they used to term in those days, I think they're prefects now, but they're monitors. Yes. Used to help the teacher.
\par I:\tab You told me the teachers emphasised correctness of speech?
\par GB:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they emphasise other things like cleanliness or punctuality?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. Yes, and a red mark if you were late and all that business, oh yes, oh yes, they didn't like that. And of course they wanted to know why you were late and - and if you were absent they wanted to know why you were, but in my time I
 can't remember much of the truancy that goes on now. No.
\par I:\tab If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par GB:\tab Oh well, if it was something that they thought was very bad you'd get a smack and if it was worse than that you'd - you'd get - the cane.
\par I:\tab Girls used to be caned as well?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of offence would merit the cane?
\par GB:\tab Well suppose you'd been - there'd been a - a - when you used the cloakroom, if you kept
 - someone would keep causing a disturbance in the cloakroom and all that business and then it become like a little skirmish, then - you'd have - two or three of you got the cane, because - they couldn't always find out who it was because nobody said it -
 would agree that it was them so - they used to give the pair of you - but by and large it wasn't too bad, I don't think it did me any harm to be corrected anyway.
\par I:\tab Did they used to give you lines or make you stay in after school that sort of thing?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. Oh fifty wasn't so bad but - I must do as I am told a hundred times. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par GB:\tab No. No, nothing at all much, no.
\par I:\tab Did they ever visit the school or meet the teachers?
\par GB:\tab I can't remember my mother or father - no, my father never but I can't even remember my mother ever doing it, no. 'Cos we just went to school to learn - we had two complete lives, home and school.
\par I:\tab Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own or not?
\par GB:\tab 
Yes, well we had - we had a couple of them that - that came from the - you know shops, and they - we - of course we used to be envious of them 'cos they dressed much nicer than we did and there was - I think it - there was only one girl that used to wear
 a drill slip and we was all jealous - jealous of her. Oh a lovely drill slip and all that, we all wanted one of them but never got it. No, they - but then by and large they were from the same type of homes. You knew all the school - all children who live
d round your - where you lived all went to the same school you see.
\par I:\tab Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par GB:\tab Sometimes, yes, this girl I said that had a - made a - and she spoke nicely and come from good pare
nts, she was made like - anything that was - she was - if the teacher had to go out the class she would be the one that was put out the front to make sure that we be - supposed to behaved. But when she used to go out there we used to - we used to have spe
lling lessons then. All the words up on to - them they used to have a big pointer and we learnt to spell you see.
\par I:\tab Did you feel they picked her out because she was nicely dressed?
\par GB:\tab Well I - I think so but mind she was a nice girl, I mean, I don't think it was all that but she was a nice girl. 'Course we were envious of her though, I don't think we were envious of her, we were envious of her drill slip.
\par I:\tab Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par GB:\tab Now this I can't remember. I can't - I can't reme
mber them, getting into a - like I see they do at school now - they might have been but I cannot remember whether they used to get in groups and - and fight or anything like that, but I don't think so because - and then we never had any supervision in the
 - in the playground either. There was never anybody - someone might fall over but - no.
\par I:\tab Do you remember any children being left out of things for any reason?
\par GB:\tab Well there were some - there were quiet - very quiet children that would go and sit in the 
corner and have their own - and then there used to be them where they used to get two that would be very fond of one another sort of thing and all get one they would get off together and do that, but - by and large we used to play skipping rope and ball a
nd all that.
\par I:\tab You don't remember like charity children being shunned?
\par GB:\tab No. No, as a matter of fact it was the other way round. If we had anything that they didn't well we'd have a - if anybody gave us an orange, 'cos we very often used to get specked f
ruit give us you know by the greengrocer and that. Well we take it in a bag and we share it all between us. Yes.
\par I:\tab How old were you when you left school?
\par GB:\tab Thirteen.
\par I:\tab Would you have stayed longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par GB:\tab Yes, I'd have been there now if I'd have had the chance. I'm not kidding, I do, I - I regret very much not having an education.
\par I:\tab Did you attend any part-time education afterwards, any evening classes?
\par GB:\tab Well I tried to go, yes, I did join evening classes. But there again I was stopped because after a while they wanted to go out and I'd got to mind the children and - see, and that stopped. But - oh I would have loved to have had an education.

\par I:\tab Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par GB:\tab Yes. 
Rather. Yes I did. I'm a - I can - I know how to say yes and not - not yeah, no and instead of not now and all that, and I did learn all that sort of thing. Because we used to have - the kind of lessons like that where we were taught to say the right word
s
. Used to have kind of things called a diction but - you know they would have diction but - I always used to listen to the teacher and she used to pronounce the words and show you how to do it and I've always tried, I've been - as far as I could to keep i
t up. I don't speak very good now I know but - I wish I did.
\par I:\tab While you were still at school did you have any part-time job or means of earning regular money?
\par GB:\tab No. My job's to mind the children.
\par I:\tab How did you get your first full-time job, do you remember?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Round where the back from where we used to live there used to be a collar place where they make collars you know and - and shirts and things. Well - there was always - notices up, see. And you went round, you just went in. If they wanted you 
they took you and if they didn't - two and six a week.
\par I:\tab What did you have to do at this first job?
\par GB:\tab Well - this first job was - they used - in those days, I don't know what they do now but in those days - the soft collars that they used to wear on the - separate from the shirts in the old days.
\par I:\tab What hours did you work at this job?
\par GB:\tab Eight 'til six, hour lunch.
\par I:\tab How about Saturday, any Saturday work?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes to - 'til twelve.
\par I:\tab Did you have any holidays with pay on this job?
\par GB:\tab You must be joking. We didn't get any pay with the work we did let alone - no, no pay - no pay, and if you had - if it was Easter or anything you just - they stopped your money.
\par I:\tab And at the time did you feel it was a fair wage or not?
\par GB:\tab Well you never knowed any di
fferent did you. You see we had nothing - anything else to compare with it so you just - well you was glad to get the half a crown 'cos you cold get quite a bit with half a crown you know when you give it to mum. Tuppence a week pocket money and you - oh 
yes. It went a long way. Two pence - two pence on a speck on a Saturday. Yes, but - that - then you could do even something with tuppence in those days.
\par I:\tab And felt quite happy about it at the time?
\par GB:\tab Oh we were - oh quite pleased about - think it was helping to - helping to raise the - standard of living as I understand it's called now.
\par I:\tab How did you get on with the people you worked with at that place?
\par GB:\tab Well - all right because I'm a very gregarious person, I like people. Yes
\par I:\tab You've always got on well with the people you've we worked with?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Well - well you always have - anybody has a tip up sometimes, I mean, you can't be always friendly and things like that, I do in the long run, by and large I like - I like people so I get on with 'em all right.
\par I:\tab How long did you work at this job?
\par GB:\tab Oh about a year.
\par I:\tab How did your employer treat you?
\par GB:\tab Well the foreman that's all you had. All right, yes, easy come easy go, as long as you were - long as you were keeping doing this nobody bothered you, long as you do it - did it you see.
\par I:\tab How did you feel about the work, did you like it or dislike it?
\par GB:\tab Well I didn't care much about it, all I knew that I was earning a few shillings that's all.
\par I:\tab After this first year in the collar factory where did you go to from there?
\par GB:\tab Well that fetch - that fetches us into - in the 1913, well what it - oh I know 
- there was a - I went - I worked in a - oh well I went from there to make an awful lot more money, making - the war was on - making gas masks for the soldiers for the war, 1914 war. And I used to put the - with a pair of pliers and wires used to put the 
pieces - the mouthpieces on. And I worked on - on that until the war ended.
\par I:\tab How much did you get at this place?
\par GB:\tab Oh - glory, twenty-six shillings a week.
\par I:\tab That ways a difference wasn't it?
\par GB:\tab Was it?
\par I:\tab How did you get this job?
\par GB:\tab Oh well, they were calling for people to help for the war you see, oh yes.
\par I:\tab What hours did you work on this job, were the hours any better or worse?
\par GB:\tab No, 'round 'bout the same. Used to get - the only thing is we used to get - instead of an hour for lunch we used to 
get - hour and a half, you know. Because there were a lot of elder - lot of women that had children to see to and so that they could get to do - they gave - made it the hour and a half.
\par I:\tab What did you feel about these wages?
\par GB:\tab Oh they were - they were -
 of course my - that was lovely for my mum. Oh yes, oh yes, things began to look up then and then - you see, then - that - that my sister - two years younger than me, she - came-out to work you see. Things were beginning to look very much brighter for us 
then.
\par I:\tab How much of this twenty-six shillings did you give your mother?
\par GB:\tab All of it, and then she used to give us back so - what she thought each week. She used to buy our clothes and that you see, some weeks - some weeks if you - if you - you used to ge
t five shillings, I've known her get seven and six back. You see, it's just how things were. But she was very fair. Oh yes. But then of course we all started having a little bit better clothing and - and little bit better food and everything like that, al
l made a difference. Of course my father was in the Army. He was a sapper in the Royal Engineers, my father.
\par I:\tab How did your employer treat you at this place?
\par GB:\tab Oh well. as long as you kept on doing your week, we had a supervisor there and there's a - and
 examiners, 'cos if you - if the work wasn't quite right it used to come back, but apart from that it - as long as you kept on and - 'course there wasn't all this stopping five minutes for tea, you had no tea breaks you know. If you had a cup of tea or an
ything it was bought round and you drank it as you worked you see.
\par I:\tab Did you like the work there?
\par GB:\tab Yes. Yes, it was and there was - there, was - we got quite - I - my understanding of life was fully made clear to me there. Because they were married wome
n and all that and they used to talk and - they used to forget that there were young ears listening and I - that's where I learnt - yes, that's right, and my gran, yes, used to go and ask my gran all about it afterwards. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did going out to work after your attitude to school at all?
\par GB:\tab No, still wanted to go to school. I've got a - I don't know, I - I like - I like learning, I like reading, I like books and my strongest point was geography. I wanted to go - I wanted to see all over the world, I've bee
n a bit since, but only since I've been sixty. Never before.
\par I:\tab What jobs have you done since the First World War that takes us up to 1918?
\par GB:\tab Well, yes, well - well when - when we came - when I came out of that - my -
 'course a that finished that job, because naturally the war - everybody was looking for jobs and - I - I had an aunt that used to work in - a brace and belt firm, she was the manageress and - and I lost - I dropped all that money and went to - learn the 
t
rade and - at the age I was and - at sixteen shillings a week. And I learnt to be - and I became within a year - year I became sample hand. At bracing, you know the braces, 'cos you don't wear sock suspenders now braces and belts and - and all the laces -
 
'cos one of the braces on the market now is my invention. And I got - 'course I did it at the firm I only got five shillings for it. Do you know the pair of braces with the long - where the - goes over the shoulders and between the back there's a long pie
c
e to - a tall man like you would need 'em, well that was one of my inventions, 'cos I had a very tall uncle and he - he always grumbled about his braces and when we - we used to have a - a Friday afternoon where we used to try new things out and he used t
o
 tell me about that and it was through him drawing sort of a thing that we thought would happen that I suggested they made these and they made these and they took on immediately, when the travellers went out with 'em they - they couldn't cope hardly with 
the orders, for tall - very tall men.
\par I:\tab What would you call this trade, machinist?
\par GB:\tab Yes, I was a - I was termed a brace and belt machinist.
\par I:\tab How long did you work there?
\par GB:\tab Oh until after I was married. I stayed there until after I was married, until I was going to have my daughter. My daughter was born in 1925.
\par I:\tab Did you stop work then?
\par GB:\tab Well I did for some years. Until she got big enough and then I used to do all sorts of odd jobs, I used to go and - help - women that were going to have babies, 
I used to be the woman used to go in and do the work in the house with the - with the nurse you see, that sort of thing. Anything to earn money you see.
\par I:\tab Have you done any other sort of work since?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, during this war, I worked on the railway.
\par I:\tab Was this full-time or part-time?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, full-time, love. No, full-time. I started - I started in 1940, and I didn't come off 'til 1958.
\par I:\tab What did you do there?
\par GB:\tab First of all I started out as a - guard - porter and then I went on from then I was taught to be a guard and I was a guard for eight years an the back of the train.
\par I:\tab Which route were you on?
\par GB:\tab I worked for the Southern and I was on - and I took trains - everywhere on the southern - on the southern circuit, electric, not to - for the c
oast. Yes. Yes, yes. The ones that - you know - that go down - what they - where the commuters use, all those, oh yes, I've worked on - worked those. Yes.
\par I:\tab Since then have you done any other work?
\par GB:\tab Well I left the fifty - no, at '58, well then - and t
hen my - no, I stayed over, a little while and then I - then I retired at sixty, I paid up me stamps for a couple of years and I retired at sixty well then - my husband - went - then - my - I was going - my husband died - let me see, I retired in the Marc
h
 and my husband died in the November. And it was from then I went of to live with my daughter. Didn't work. And then I went as a housekeeper. And I was a housekeeper for a good few - many years, with an old lady. And that was in the north of England where
 I'm going back next week.
\par I:\tab How many years were you housekeeping?
\par GB:\tab I went up there - yes, wait a minute, I went up there in 19 - 19 - 1962 to 19 - 1967.
\par I:\tab Would you have preferred any other sort of occupation?
\par GB:\tab Well I never thought about it. Anytime anything came along I did it because - there again -
\par I:\tab It was necessity?
\par GB:\tab Yes, money you see, the money and - work. Mind it was a very good job I had with this lady. I'd have been with her now if she hadn't have died.
\par I:\tab Did you belong to any trade union or professional organisation?
\par GB:\tab Oh well when I worked on the railway I belonged to the N.U.R.
\par I:\tab Did you take part in any of its activities at all?
\par GB:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you feel that employers and workers had the same interests or not?
\par GB:\tab 
Well - I don't know - about that but there was an incident - where - we had a - I was I guard and we had a break - a breakdown with trains and you know you're not supposed by - then - I don't know whether it is now but - by unions you're, not supposed to 
w
ork more than twelve hours. Well I got stuck out in - terrible snow - snow storm. And I got in awful trouble with the union because I worked - I left home at quarter to ten on Saturday morning and I didn't return home 'till half past five Sunday morning a
n
d I'd booked on fourteen and a half hours and I got in awful trouble with the union, but then - what could you do. When you're down in Sevenoaks and you know that you should come back a passenger and there's no guard to bring the train back and there's a 
l
ot of women with children, well you do, you bring the train back, you see. And that's what I did and I got in awful trouble with the union about it. But when I - 'course when I went up like for the - 'bout it and explained all about it well - seeing that 
- they said, seeing that I was a woman and seeing all those - mothers and that with their children that - that paved it you see.
\par I:\tab Did you feel that there were divisions of interest among workers? Before 1918 people say that in those days there was a great division between craftsmen and labourers, do you feel this was so or not?
\par GB:\tab Well I think there was, 'cos if a man had a - a - had a skilled job, he - and - you know, he always seemed a little bit different to the man that was - 'course the labourers in 
them days were in and out of jobs all the time, going from one to the other, in my - in our - you know, in our street and our station of life if a man was a labourer - and then if a man was a labourer and there he was, another job going that was two or th
ree shillings more he would leave that job and go the other, but the craftsman didn't you see. 'Cos my father did have a good trade. If only he'd been a different man we could have had a very marvellous life.
\par I:\tab You continued to live at home after you left school?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. Oh yes, yes.
\par I:\tab Did starting full-time work change your relationship with your parents at all?
\par GB:\tab No, not really. It - it - we lost - when I began to get older I lost - that - touch of being with younger children because the next ones 
that were coming along took over from me you see. I lost that. But - and then of course after a while of course there were no more children coming along so then we all began to get - up together, but we all got on pretty well together, yes. 'Cos my mother
 saw to that, she wouldn't have any - any upheaval in the house. Really she was pretty good, she used to be able to - she had an eyebrow and it - when it used to go up, oh dear, if it went up twice that was your lot.
\par I:\tab So after you left school you began to have a bit more freedom?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. My mother was a rare one for - rare one for keep - we'd got to be at ten o'clock at night, right 'til the day - night before I was married. Yes. But - I used to - I used to play - I learnt - I had a cousin and - well I
 had a sweetheart that died and - when he died my cousin used to ask em over there, they used to live at Lee Green. And it was there that I learnt to play tennis. You know, and I used to go - in the summer used to go there weekends to play tennis in the p
ark and - that was nice, I liked doing that.
\par I:\tab I suppose your life changed quite a lot when you didn't have the young ones to look after?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. No, not when I didn't - I didn't have the young ones.
\par I:\tab Did you spend your Sundays and differently after you started work, did you stop gong to Sunday school?
\par GB:\tab Yes. We all stopped going to Sunday school, yes, we used to go - visiting our - aunts that lived a little way away so that you could have the bus ride. And in the summer - 'cos I had a - my boy - fi
rst boy that died - I used to go - we used to go on the top of a open top bus to go out to Loughton, Epping Forest and, all those places you know. But in the winter - in the winter we used to - we used to stay in a lot, we used to - my - first boy, he use
d
 to play - liked to play dominoes and darts and so he bought them and - and left them in the house and then - then one day he bought a - a - what do they call it, they call it ping-pong now don't they or - table tennis, that was ping-pong then, yes, ping-
pong, yes, he bought that and used to - but he was very good, he died when he was twenty, he was very good with the young ones, used to teach them and all. They used to love him.
\par I:\tab So your life became much gayer?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes. Oh yes, and then the children b
egan to grow up, yes, they used to go to, as I said, we used to go to the - to the cinema and used to go to the theatre. Every Saturday my - my boy, the one that died, used to go to the - the - in the in the gallery in the London - in a London theatre eve
ry Saturday night. Used to go and line up for the gallery and - oh we - I loved it.
\par I:\tab These friends at this time were they new friends or were they old friends from your schooldays, did you make new acquaintances at this time?
\par GB:\tab Well you made - acquaintance of people where you worked you got to know them you know, you got asked to visit them, all that sort of thing. Yes. New friends, yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Your met these at work did you?
\par GB:\tab Yes. That's right.
\par I:\tab Did you ever bring your friend's home at all, you used to bring this boyfriend home didn't you?
\par GB:\tab Oh yes, Cyril - my Cyril. Yes, but no others, no, nobody else.
\par I:\tab Did your parents expect to meet your friends?
\par GB:\tab No, not really. No.
\par I:\tab Did they expect to know where you were going when you went out?
\par GB:\tab Oh - not - they - not they, mum, yes. Yes. On the doorstep ten o'clock or else, and we never - and not one of us ever failed to obey 'cos we know what we'd get.
\par I:\tab Did you take an interest in politics at this time?
\par GB:\tab No, never even knew what politics wer
e, we didn't, no. No. We used to go - I tell you what we'd do when we was kids, we used to go round when he - 'course they don't have it now but all the schools used to have all the big banners up and everything and us kids used to have these things and w
e
 used to go round singing about whoever was on it and - and they used to encourage us, the - the candidates used to encourage us, used to give us sweets to stand out and shout out their name and all that sort of thing. Mind it was - it was good fun. Bette
r fun than the kids get now.
\par I:\tab What else can you tell us about teenage life at that time?
\par GB:\tab Well we - we - Well of course it was - yes, it wasn't called teenage was it? Well we always had - even when we went to work you know we came home - we always had 
chores. All chores, oh yes, we kept our own bedrooms clean and - and we helped mum with the ironing and all that, certain nights a week we - we had to stay in and do these jobs. Yes, oh yes, we always had our chores right up to the - as I say right 'till 
t
he day we were married we had our little chores to do each week but - of course - well - we - us girls used to get together and we used to think well mum was getting on, it was about time mum had a bit of an easy life. So we used to - we used to between u
s
 arrange what we would do so that we were helping, say, well leave the ironing, we'll do it when we come home, we'll do this and we'll do that, and then of course all working together it was - easy you see. Oh yes, it was much easier when we went to work.
 Yes, I'll say so.
\par I:\tab What did you used to do when you went out with your friends in the evening, today if boys and girls want to meet they go in a coffee bar.
\par GB:\tab Oh no, there was no such thing as coffee bars then. Well - well - well - well, you've heard o
